ed Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fychan","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maredudd Fychan ap Maredudd was born about 1260, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Maredudd ap Richard, was 48 and his mother, Gwladus ferch Meurig, was 46. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Elen ferch Maredudd."},"et":{"about 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1214–Male":"1214–Surnud","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","ABT    1286":"umbes 1286","1245":"1245","1332":"1332","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","ABT    1290":"umbes 1290","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","of,Derllys cmt,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1214–Male":"1214–Kuollut","1216–Female":"1216–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","ABT    1286":"noin 1286","1245":"1245","1332":"1332","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","ABT    1290":"noin 1290","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","of,Derllys cmt,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1260–":"environ 1260–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1245–Female":"1245–Décédée","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1290–Female":"1290–Décé